 revise, you are telling a story to yourself...over and over again.\n\n- Kai\n|\nOnly a writer 'with Bennett's craft and brass could manage to praise and insult his readers at the same time.\n\n- Harold Holzer, Lincoln and the Power of the Press: The War for Public Opinion\n|\nHelloooo? I just made some changes in my life, and if I don't get back to you as soon as possible, then guess what? You were one of those changes.\n\n- Rumiko\n|\nHave you ever tried thinking of God as a person instead of an all-powerful vending machine that never gives you the right amount of change? He has feelings too, you know.\n\n- Angela N. Blount, Once Upon a Road Trip\n|\nThe shadow demons (fears) you've been avoiding keep you stuck in a rut, a prisoner in your own life - it's time to break free and shine!\n\n- Sharon Kirstin, The Answers Within\n|\nIs there any success, without the soundness of mind?\n\n- Lailah\n|\nThere's an old saying that applies to me: you can't lose a game if you don't play the game. (Act 1, scene 4)\n\n- William Shakespeare, Romeo and Juliet\n|\nTo live entirely without a goal! I have glimpsed this state, and have often attained it, without managing to remain there: I am too weak for such happiness.\n\n- Emil\n|\nEvery concept of reality is all in our head, belief is what makes truth.\n\n- Christy\n|\nEven intellectuals should have learned by now that objective rationality is not the default position of the human mind, much less the bedrock of human affairs.\n\n- Roy Blount Jr., Long Time Leaving: Dispatches from Up South\n|\nYou can't have living without dying. So you can't call it living, what we got. We just are, we just be, like rocks beside the road.\n\n- Natalie Babbitt, Tuck Everlasting\n|\nIn thoughts, be wise. In speech, be cautious. In sentiment, be positive. In actions, be prudent.\n\n- Matshona\n|\nEach affects the other, and the other affects the next, and the world is full of stories, but the stories are all one.\n\n- Mitch Albom, The Five People 